{"id":"1501.07258","submitter":"Lionel Levine","authors":"Lionel Levine, Mathav Murugan, Yuval Peres, Baris Evren Ugurcan","title":"The divisible sandpile at critical density","comments":"34 pages, to appear in Annales Henri Poincare","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s00023-015-0433-x","report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR cond-mat.stat-mech math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The divisible sandpile starts with i.i.d. random variables (\"masses\") at the\nvertices of an infinite, vertex-transitive graph, and redistributes mass by a\nlocal toppling rule in an attempt to make all masses at most 1. The process\nstabilizes almost surely if m<1 and it almost surely does not stabilize if m>1,\nwhere $m$ is the mean mass per vertex. The main result of this paper is that in\nthe critical case m=1, if the initial masses have finite variance, then the\nprocess almost surely does not stabilize. To give quantitative estimates on a\nfinite graph, we relate the number of topplings to a discrete biLaplacian\nGaussian field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Jan 2015 20:15:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 13 Aug 2015 01:15:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-06-29"}
